<h2 class="wiley-section-title">Learning Objectives</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Understand key elements of traditional Māori storytelling structures</li>
            <li>Apply <span class="maori-term">pūrākau</span> (Māori narratives) techniques to modern creative writing</li>
            <li>Create an original narrative using Māori storytelling frameworks</li>
            <li>Reflect on how cultural narratives shape identity and worldview</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="activity">
        <h2 class="wiley-section-title">Cultural Context & Safety Notes</h2>
        <p><strong>Cultural Context:</strong> Traditional Māori narratives (<span class="maori-term">pūrākau</span>) often follow structures that differ from Western storytelling. Key elements include:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><span class="maori-term">Whakapapa</span> (genealogical connections)</li>
            <li>Cyclical time rather than linear progression</li>
            <li>Deep connection to <span class="maori-term">whenua</span> (land) and natural world</li>
            <li>Teaching through metaphor rather than direct moral statements</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Safety Notes:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Some traditional stories may be <span class="maori-term">tapu</span> (sacred) to specific iwi</li>
            <li>Always acknowledge the source of any traditional stories used</li>
            <li>Encourage students to create original stories rather than retell sacred narratives</li>
            <li>Consult with local <span class="maori-term">kaumātua</span> (elders) if unsure about appropriate content</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="activity">
        <h2 class="wiley-section-title">Lesson Activities</h2>
        
        <h3>1. Understanding Māori Story Structures (20 mins)</h3>
        <div class="interactive">
            <p><strong>Group Discussion:</strong> Compare a traditional Māori story (e.g., <em>Māui and the Sun</em>) with a Western fairy tale. What differences do you notice in:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Story structure?</li>
                <li>Character development?</li>
                <li>Relationship to nature?</li>
                <li>Purpose of the story?</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>2. Key Elements of <span class="maori-term">Pūrākau</span> (15 mins)</h3>
        <p>Introduce the <span class="maori-term">Pūrākau Framework</span>:</p>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Kupu whakataki</strong> (Introduction) - Establishes connections to people/place</li>
            <li><strong>Huarahi</strong> (Journey) - Often involves challenges or tests</li>
            <li><strong>Taumata</strong> (Climax) - Moment of transformation</li>
            <li><strong>Hokinga</strong> (Return) - Brings new knowledge back to community</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>3. Writing Activity (30 mins)</h3>
        <div class="interactive">
            <p><strong>Create Your Own Story:</strong> Using the <span class="maori-term">Pūrākau Framework</span>, write a modern story that:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Connects to a place important to you</li>
                <li>Includes a journey (physical or emotional)</li>
                <li>Teaches a lesson without stating it directly</li>
                <li>Uses natural elements symbolically</li>
            </ul>
            <p><em>Example starter:</em> "Long before the highway was built, when the hills still whispered to each other at dawn..."</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="activity">
        <h2 class="wiley-section-title">Assessment Suggestions</h2>
        <p>Use this checklist to assess student narratives:</p>
        <ul class="checklist">
            <li>Clear use of <span class="maori-term">pūrākau</span> structure (introduction, journey, climax, return)</li>
            <li>Meaningful connection to place/environment</li>
            <li>Effective use of symbolic elements</li>
            <li>Originality and creativity in modern application</li>
            <li>Cultural respect and appropriateness</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Alternative Assessment:</strong> Students record an oral telling of their story, focusing on delivery style inspired by traditional storytelling.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="activity">
        <h2 class="wiley-section-title">Extension Activities</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Research and compare storytelling structures from another indigenous culture</li>
            <li>Create an illustrated version of the story using traditional Māori design elements</li>
            <li>Develop the narrative into a short play incorporating <span class="maori-term">waiata</span> (songs) and movement</li>
            <li>Write a reflection on how using this structure changed their approach to storytelling</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="activity">
        <h2 class="wiley-section-title">Adaptations for Diverse Learners</h2>
        <p><strong>For students needing support:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Provide a graphic organizer of the <span class="maori-term">pūrākau</span> structure</li>
            <li>Offer sentence starters for each section</li>
            <li>Allow oral storytelling instead of written</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>For English Language Learners:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Use visual prompts for key concepts</li>
            <li>Provide bilingual vocabulary lists</li>
            <li>Encourage use of their first language in planning stages</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="activity">
        <h2 class="wiley-section-title">Teacher Implementation Guide</h2>
        <h3>Before the Lesson:</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Familiarize yourself with examples of <span class="maori-term">pūrākau</span></li>
            <li>Prepare printed copies of a traditional Māori story for analysis</li>
            <li>Create a shared digital document for collaborative brainstorming</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>During the Lesson:</h3>
        <ol>
            <li>Begin with a <span class="maori-term">karakia</span> (optional) to set purposeful atmosphere</li>
            <li>Use the comparison activity to highlight cultural differences in storytelling</li>
            <li>Explicitly teach the <span class="maori-term">pūrākau</span> framework using visual aids</li>
            <li>Circulate during writing time, prompting students to consider symbolic elements</li>
        </ol>
        <h3>After the Lesson:</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Create a class anthology of stories</li>
            <li>Invite students to share stories in small groups</li>
            <li>Display stories with accompanying artwork in classroom or school space</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

